"1335–":"1335.–preminuo","1335–Male":"1335.–preminuo","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1358–Female":"1358–preminula","1375–Male":"1375.–preminuo","1305–Male":"1305–preminuo","1315–Female":"1315–preminula","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1335":"1335.","before 1335":"prije 1335.","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1375":"1375.","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europe","England":"England"},"cs":{"1335–":"1335–Zesnulý","1335–Male":"1335–Zesnulý","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Zesnulá","1375–Male":"1375–Zesnulý","1305–Male":"1305–Zesnulý","1315–Female":"1315–Zesnulá","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","before 1335":"před 1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europe","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"1335–":"1335–Afdød","1335–Male":"1335–Afdød","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Afdød","1375–Male":"1375–Afdød","1305–Male":"1305–Afdød","1315–Female":"1315–Afdød","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","before 1335":"før 1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europe","England":"England"},"nl":{"1335–":"1335–Overleden","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Overleden","1375–Male":"1375–Overleden","1305–Male":"1305–Overleden","1315–Female":"1315–Overleden","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","before 1335":"vóór 1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europa","England":"England"},"en":{"1335–":"1335–Deceased","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Deceased","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","before 1335":"before 1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Pope was born in 1335, in England, his father, Milo Pope, was 31 and his mother, Miss Arden, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Maria Tibetot. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1335–":"1335–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","before 1335":"enne 1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1375":"